We have different variable types:

  • Price, Age_08_04, KM, HP, Doors, Quarterly_Tax, and Guarantee_Period are numerical variables.
  • Fuel_Type is a categorical variable with three levels (CNG, Diesel and Petrol)
  • Automatic, Mfr_Guarantee, Airco, Automatic_airco, CD_Player, Powered_Windows, Sport_Model and Tow_Bar are all dummy variables.

We have a dummy variable for Airco and one for Automatic_airco. If everything is normal, it shouldnt be possible to have Airco = 0 and Automatic_airco = 1, this would be contradictory, as it would mean the car has no air conditioning but has automatic air conditioning. We check that there are no rows with this situation in our data:

Clearly, CNG and Diesel fuels are much rarer than Petrol in this data set.

For a linear regression, Fuel_Type needs to be converted to two dummy variables, one for Petrol and one for Diesel. We dont need a dummy variable for CGR, as it would be a perfect linear combination of the other two dummies. The linear regression lm() function takes care of this by itself, so we do not need to manually transform Fuel_Type into dummies.

We now split our data into training (50%), validation (30%) and test (20%) sets.

set.seed(111)  # set seed for reproducing the partition

# generating training set index
train.index <- sample(c(1:nrow(ToyotaCorolla)), 0.5*nrow(ToyotaCorolla))
# generating validation set index taken from the complementary of training set
valid.index <- sample(setdiff(c(1:nrow(ToyotaCorolla)), train.index), 0.3*nrow(ToyotaCorolla))
# defining test set index as complementary of (train.index + valid.index)
test.index  <- setdiff(c(1:nrow(ToyotaCorolla)), union(train.index, valid.index))

# creating data tables Train, Valid and Test using the indexes
Train <- ToyotaCorolla[train.index, ]
Valid <- ToyotaCorolla[valid.index, ]
Test <- ToyotaCorolla[test.index, ]

# removing indexes as they aren't used anymore
rm(train.index, valid.index, test.index)

We will scale the numerical variables with respect to the training set. It is better to scale numerical variables so we can compare the \(\hat\beta\) coefficients obtained with the regression on a fair ground. Otherwise, the size of each \(\hat\beta\) coefficient will be influenced by the scale of the associated variable.

# preProcess from the caret package to compute means and sd on Train for scaling
norm.values <- preProcess(ToyotaCorolla[, c(1,2,3,5,7,8,10)], method=c("center", "scale"))
# scaling Train, Valid and Test
Train[, c(1,2,3,5,7,8,10)] <- predict(norm.values, Train[, c(1,2,3,5,7,8,10)])
Valid[, c(1,2,3,5,7,8,10)] <- predict(norm.values, Valid[, c(1,2,3,5,7,8,10)])
 Test[, c(1,2,3,5,7,8,10)] <- predict(norm.values,  Test[, c(1,2,3,5,7,8,10)])

We are now ready to perform a linear regression.

# we compute the linear regression with lm, using Price as our dependent variable
# ~ . means that we use every other variable as predictor

Toyota.LM <- lm(Price ~ ., data = Train)

We can see that most variables have small \(p\)-values and the \(p\)-value of the \(F\)-statistic (which acts as a kind of collective \(p\)-value in multilinear regressions) is also extremely small. This indicates that our coefficients have a significant impact on our dependent variable (Price). Airco and Mfr_Guarantee have \(p\)-values bigger than 0.05, so they might not have a significant impact.

The standard error \(\hat\sigma\) is 0.34, it isnt very small but not too big either. The \(R^2\) and \(R^2_{adj}\) values are quite close to 0.9, which means that roughly 90% of variation in price is explained by our model. This is a good value.

1 What appear to be the three or four most important car specifications for predicting the cars price?

The variables whose \(\hat\beta\) coefficients have the greatest impact are:

  • Automatic_airco (0.89)
  • Age_08_04 (-0.55)
  • Fuel_TypeDiesel (0.63) and Fuel_TypePetrol (0.52)

Automatic_airco and the two Fuel_Type dummies have a positive impact on price, whereas age Age_08_04 has a negative impact. This seems logical, as older cars tend to be sold for lower prices.

We can note that KM and Tow_Bar have a negative influence of the retail price (however, \(\hat\beta_{TowBar}\) is quite small, so the influence isnt very impactful).

2 Using metrics you consider useful, assess the performance of the model in predicting prices.

First, we will construct a data table which contains the Price column from our validation set and the predicted prices of the validation set which we get through our linear model Toyota.LM.

We will scale back the two price columns to their original scales. The mean and standard error of Price (from our training data) are stored inside the norm.values object we had created:

norm.values$mean[1] # mean of price
##    Price 
## 10730.82
norm.values$std[1]  # standard deviation of price
##    Price 
## 3626.965

When we standardized, we had \[Price_{norm} = \dfrac{Price - \mu}{\sigma}\] Thus, we will compute now \[Price = \sigma \cdot Price_{norm} + \mu\]

We also add a column which computes the residuals by subtracting the first two columns together once they are denormalized.

# creating the data table by taking the Price column from Valid and
# using the predict() function to predict prices of Valid with Toyota.LM
ValidAccuracy <- data.table("Values" = Valid$Price, "PredictedValues" = predict(Toyota.LM, Valid))
# scaling back the two columns to their original scales
ValidAccuracy <- ValidAccuracy[, Values := Values*norm.values$std[1] + norm.values$mean[1] ]
ValidAccuracy <- ValidAccuracy[, PredictedValues :=
                                 PredictedValues*norm.values$std[1] + norm.values$mean[1] ]
# adding Residuals column by subtracting Values - PredictedValues
ValidAccuracy <- ValidAccuracy[, Residuals := Values - PredictedValues]
# displaying the first rows of ValidAccuracy
head(ValidAccuracy)

The boxplot shows that almost all residuals are inside \([-3000,3000]\) and the median is close to 0, as we would expect.

The histogram shows that the residuals are bell-shaped, but the extreme values seem to be spreading further away than for a normal distribution. We can clearly see that the main portion of residuals is between \([-1500,1500]\). This means that the price estimation will vary by \(\pm 1500 \) in the majority of cases.

The Residuals versus Predicted Values plot shows that again residuals concentrate around zero. Furthermore, we can see that extreme positive residuals correspond to higher values of predicted prices, whereas extreme negative residuals correspond to lower predicted prices. Let us recall that residuals are defined as Values - PredictedValues, meaning that a positive residual is an underestimation of price while a negative residual is an overestimation of price. Then, we can deduce that the extreme positive residuals are cars with higher prices which are underestimated and extreme negative residuals are cars with lower prices which are overestimated.

The QQ plot of residuals shows that the residuals are straying away from a normal distribution when we get towards extreme values. However, the book states that the model can be very good for prediction even if residuals arent normally distributed. We are more concerned with normality when we are trying to fit a regression model.

Now, we will use the accuracy function from the forecast package. This function computes ME, RMSE, MAE, MPE and MAPE.

Let us recall what these prediction measures are. We cite the book (chapter 5.2, page 119). We denote the residuals by \(r = y - \hat y\).

  1. ME (Mean Error) gives an indication of whether the predictions are on average over- or under-predicting the outcome variable. \[ME = \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n}r_i\]
  2. RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) is similar to the standard error of estimate in linear regression, except that it is computed on the validation data rather than on the training data. \[RMSE = \sqrt{\dfrac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}r_i^2}\]
  3. MAE (Mean Absolute Error) gives the magnitude of the average absolute error. \[MAE = \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n}|r_i|\]
  4. MPE (Mean Percentage Error) gives the percentage score of how predictions deviate from the actual values (on average), taking into account the direction of the error. \[MPE = 100 \cdot \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \dfrac{r_i}{y_i}\]
  5. MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error) gives a percentage score of how predictions deviate (on average) from the actual values. \[MAPE = 100 \cdot \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left| \dfrac{r_i}{y_i}\right|\]
# computing accuracy measures for valid
accuracy(ValidAccuracy$PredictedValues, ValidAccuracy$Values)
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set -95.91656 1214.533 900.5001 -2.108908 9.049204

We can deduce that

  1. On average, the model over-predicts price by \(96\) (recall that negative residuals mean we are overestimating).
  2. Predictions will vary from true values by \(\pm 1215 \) most of the time.
  3. The magnitude of errors is of \(901\) on average.
  4. Predictions will vary from true values by \(-2.11\%\) on average (direction of errors is taken into account).
  5. The magnitude of errors will vary by \(9.05\%\) on average.

Residuals in our test set have a minimal value that is twice as small as the minimum of our validation set! Let us see if this difference will impact the accuracy measures.

# computing accuracy measures for valid and test in order to compare
accuracy(ValidAccuracy$PredictedValues, ValidAccuracy$Values)
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set -95.91656 1214.533 900.5001 -2.108908 9.049204
accuracy(TestAccuracy$PredictedValues, TestAccuracy$Values)
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set -152.8982 1203.863 946.8009 -2.565436 9.505479

ME is smaller than with the validation set, suggesting a bigger tendency to overestimate price on average (\(-153\) instead of \(-96\)). However, the four other measures stayed close to their old values.

In conclusion, this linear regression model gives good but not extraordinary results.

If it is satisfactory or good enough will depend on the requirements and goals of the car dealership, the main issue being if the variance in predictions is too large or not (RMSE being a little more than \(1200\), we would need to assess with management if this value is acceptable or not).

The biggest residual errors are around \(\pm 5500\) which is quite a large value. High positive residual values would maybe be less harmful, since it means there would be more profit than expected, but a negative residual of \(5000\) can surely represent a significant discrepancy with the prediction, resulting in profit loss. Once again, management would assess if such extreme errors are acceptable, or if a different model with smaller residuals should be tried out instead. At least, looking at residuals histograms we can see that there arent more negative than positive residuals, meaning that the overall impact of negative residuals would cancel out with the positive ones.

The tendency of the model to slightly overestimate prices is also a flaw. In my opinion, it would be better to have a slight underestimation of prices (and thus profit) than the contrary, as overestimating means the projections are a bit too enthusiastic. However, the overestimation seems to be under \(200\), which compared to the overall price of a car isnt too impactful.
